HANTAVIRUS - AMERICAS (10): USA (COLORADO)
******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 2 Nov 2020 04:03 PM EST
Source: Fox 8 [edited]
https://myfox8.com/news/hiker-with-symptoms-similar-to-covid-19-diagnosed-with-rare-disease/


SR feels lucky to be alive after several visits to the hospital in October [2020]. She had several symptoms that overlap with COVID-19, but was eventually diagnosed with a hantavirus [infection] -- an extremely rare and often fatal disease.

"I had a high fever, headaches," she said.

SR said her symptoms began a few days after a hiking and camping trip on the Colorado Trail. She took a COVID-19 test, which came back negative as her symptoms worsened. "I had low oxygen. I went to the hospital, assumed I had COVID, again ... negative," she said.

After a 2nd trip to the hospital, medical experts tested for several influenzas and did imaging screenings before a pulmonologist determined her diagnosis was the rare hantavirus [infection].

"I had fluid around my lungs, fluid around my heart," she said. "Because it's so rare, I was actually kind of blown away. I actually got this disease and didn't die."

According to the CDC, hantavirus is spread through the air by deer mice droppings or fluids.

Medical experts do not know where SR contracted the hantavirus, but she wants others to know the disease exists in Colorado.

"It may not be COVID," SR said. "If you have been around mice, let your doctor know about that event."

The CDC says symptoms of hantavirus [infection] can include fatigue, fever, body aches and stomach problems. According to UCHealth, there have been 151 cases in Colorado since 1993.

"I'm very grateful to our doctors and medical system for figuring this out," SR said. "I feel lucky to be on the green side. That's what I feel."

--
