[This is the 2nd case of a hantavirus infection in Colorado that ProMED has posted this year (2020). One was posted last year (2019) and ProMED posted 3 Colorado cases in 2018.

The specific circumstances under which the case above contracted the infection was not indicated but probably involved an area where mouse droppings indicated that the rodent reservoir of the virus was present. The hantavirus involved in this, and other cases in the western USA, is Sin Nombre virus (SNV). Fatalities are due to hantavirus cardiopulmonary syndrome (HPS). HPS can be very serious and progress swiftly, so patients developing the symptoms should seek medical attention at the earliest possible time.

The clinical diagnosis for the 1st 2020 case was hemorrhagic fever with renal syndrome that suggests that SEOV (Seoul orthohantavirus) was the etiological agent. Although the Colorado state diagnostic laboratory reported seropositive results for SNV, the authors of the report point out that serologic cross-reactivity makes a definitive diagnosis uncertain (see Hantavirus - Americas (03): USA (CO) 20200206.6958611).

Infected rodents shed the virus in feces, urine, and saliva. Individuals opening up cabins or storage areas that have been closed over winter or cleaning areas with signs of rodent presence should heed the precautions indicated above and those that the CDC recommends in order to avoid exposure to the virus (https://www.cdc.gov/rodents/cleaning/index.html).

Deer mice, _Peromyscus maniculatus_, are the reservoir hosts of SNV. An image can be seen at http://www.nsf.gov/news/mmg/media/images/mouse_f.jpg. - Mod.TY

HealthMap/ProMED map of Colorado, United States: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7914901,209]
